            <p>
                From the hint we have
                <md>
                    \text{gcd}(a+b, a^2+b^2)=\text{gcd}(a+b, (a+b)(a-b)+2b^2)
                </md>

                Let <m>d=\text{gcd}(a+b, a^2+b^2)</m>. Then <m>d|a+b</m>, and <m>d|(a+b)(a-b)+2b^2</m>. Since <m>d|a+b</m>, <m>d|(a+b)(a-b)</m>. It follows that <m>d|2b^2</m>
            </p>
               
            
            <p>
                We claim <m>\text{gcd}(d,b)=1</m>.  
            Suppose not, and there is a prime <m>p</m> that divides <m>d</m> and <m>b</m>.  Then <m>p|a+b</m> which implies that <m>p|a</m>. But that contradicts the assumption that <m>\text{gcd}(a,b)=1.</m>  
            </p>
           
           <p>
            If <m>\text{gcd}(d,b)=1</m>, then so too <m>\text{gcd}(d, b^2)=1</m>. Euclid's Lemmas then gives that <m>d|2</m> since <m>d|2b^2</m> and <m>\text{gcd}(d, b^2)=1.</m> If <m>d|2</m> then <m>d=1</m> or <m>d=2</m>.
                
                
            </p>
