    <subsection xml:id="Question_2_4_6">
    <title> Problem 6</title>
    <p>
        Suppose <m>\text{gcd}(a+b, ab) \neq 1</m>. Then there is some prime <m>p</m> such that <m>p|\text{gcd}(a+b, ab)</m>. We claim <m>p</m> must divide at least one of <m>a</m> or <m>b</m>.  Suppose <m>p \nmid a</m>, then <m>\text{gcd}(a,p)=1</m> and by Euclid's lemmas we'd have <m>p|b</m>.  Similarly if <m>p\nmid b</m> we'd have <m>p|a</m>. Suppose, without loss of generality, that <m>p|a</m>.  Since also, <m>p|a+b</m> we have <m>p|b</m>. This contradicts the assumption that <m>\text{gcd}(a,b)=1</m>.  Thus, it must be that <m>\text{gcd}(a+b, ab)=1.</m>
           
               
            
       
    </p>
    </subsection>
